passages.text: Developers' sales weakness extend into August

According to CRIC, the top 100 developers' contracted sales Y/Y decline narrowed mildly from - 27% in July to - 22% in August. However, this is because of a lower base. If compared to the 4- year average (2018- 21), sales in August were - 77%, same as July (- 77%), i.e., no improvement at all (Figure 1). Despite the recent easing in Beijing & Shanghai, we don't anticipate a meaningful turnaround. Against this backdrop, we expect policymakers will be forced to roll out stronger policy support (or at least a stronger narrative) over the next few months (more discussion). As we are approaching "Golden September, Silver October", we believe authorities may be incentivized to support the sector. If stronger policy materializes, the sector may see 25- 30% upside if we benchmark to the peak in October 2024. Fundamentally, we like CR Land, CR Mixe & Jinmao (note: Jinmao once again saw an outperforming +46% Y/Y sales growth in August). However, in a policy- induced rally, we see more upside in COLI & COPL (as laggards) among SOEs; and Longfor (as a high- beta name with low default risk) among non- SOEs.

- September sales may improve M/M, but the Y/Y decline may remain weak: Since both July and August are traditionally a low season (Table 3), we expect September will see a M/M improvement, but this is solely due to seasonality. On a Y/Y basis, we think the decline might continue to be weak if there is no further policy support (note: the base in 4Q will be even higher because of policy easing in September 2024).

- Top 100 developers' year-to-date sales have dropped 14% Y/Y or 70% below the average of 2018-21. For the full year of 2025, we forecast a 17% Y/Y decline among top 100 developers' sales, implying -21% Y/Y for the rest of the year. However, note that this full-year forecast is different from our 7% Y/Y decline forecast for national sales value from NBS, which has historically reported better trends than CRIC's.

- Identifying the alphas: SOEs' sales improved from -11% Y/Y in July to +10% Y/Y in August (Figure 3). In August alone, key SOEs which saw outperforming growths include C&D (+49% Y/Y), Jinmao (+46%), China Merchants Shekou (+39%) and Greentown (+23%) (Figure 8). Year-to-date (first 8 months), Jinmao has remained the notable outperformer with +26% Y/Y growth, followed by C&D (+5%) and Yuexiu (+4%) (Figure 6). For more discussion on Jinmao, please see our earlier report The earnings drop in 1H25 doesn't change the multi-year turnaround story.

- Vanke's sales remain worrying: Vanke's sales dropped 48% Y/Y in August (or -44% Y/Y YTD). The Rmb9bn sales in August is below our estimate of minimum monthly sales required (Rmb13bn) to achieve positive OCF.
